WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:01.460
All right. Good afternoon, everyone.

2
00:00:02.260 --> 00:00:06.040
My name is Steve Forman, and I'm from the City of Hope Comprehensive Cancer Center

3
00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:06.880
in Los Angeles.

4
00:00:07.900 --> 00:00:07.950
It

5
00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:12.620
has been my honor to serve as the chair of this year's selection committee for the

6
00:00:12.700 --> 00:00:16.300
AACR Joseph H. Burkenau Award for

7
00:00:16.340 --> 00:00:19.560
Outstanding Achievement in Clinical Cancer Research.

8
00:00:20.540 --> 00:00:24.340
This award was established in 1996 in collaboration with Bristol

9
00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:24.840
Myers.

10
00:00:25.800 --> 00:00:29.730
It's meant to award investigators whose work has

11
00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:32.780
profoundly advanced clinical cancer research and improved patient

12
00:00:32.920 --> 00:00:36.740
care. The award commemorates the late Joseph Burkenau,

13
00:00:36.860 --> 00:00:39.680
who was a past president and honorary member of AACR.

14
00:00:40.660 --> 00:00:44.490
His career spanned five decades and was a true pioneer in

15
00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:48.060
helping establish, at that time, chemotherapy as a transformative treatment for

16
00:00:48.100 --> 00:00:51.340
cancer, and was awarded the Lasker Prize for

17
00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:53.790
his work, particularly in Burkitt

18
00:00:53.860 --> 00:00:57.000
lymphoma. This year's honoree is a

19
00:00:57.020 --> 00:01:00.410
physician-scientist whose work has reshaped cancer diagnosis and treatment.

20
00:01:01.260 --> 00:01:05.181
The 2026 AACR Joseph Burkenau Award for Outstanding Achievement

21
00:01:05.220 --> 00:01:08.840
in Clinical Cancer Research is being presented to Dr. Luis Diaz Jr.

22
00:01:09.880 --> 00:01:13.710
Dr. Diaz serves as the Solid Tumor Oncology Division Head and

23
00:01:13.780 --> 00:01:17.340
Grayer Family Chair at Memorial Sloan Kettering in New York,

24
00:01:17.980 --> 00:01:21.540
where he leads the clinical care of cancer patients across 10 disease

25
00:01:21.620 --> 00:01:25.480
programs while conducting his own translational research that has

26
00:01:25.520 --> 00:01:27.420
reshaped cancer diagnosis and therapy.

27
00:01:27.450 --> 00:01:31.250
And I can speak very personally of the idea that there's not a

28
00:01:31.300 --> 00:01:35.260
day that doesn't go by that some of the work that you do, we use

29
00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:37.740
throughout our clinics at the City of Hope and in my own practice in

30
00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:41.560
particular. He's widely recognized for his groundbreaking work in

31
00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:45.440
tumor genomics, circulating tumor DNA, immunotherapy, which

32
00:01:45.580 --> 00:01:49.340
has, as I said, revolutionized the way we detect, monitor, and actually

33
00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:50.860
take care of people with cancer.

34
00:01:51.900 --> 00:01:55.620
Dr. Diaz has been a leader in the development of circulating tumor DNA

35
00:01:56.320 --> 00:02:00.220
as a non-invasive biomarker, demonstrating its ability to provide

36
00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:03.950
comprehensive genetic profiling that allows us to do

37
00:02:04.100 --> 00:02:07.920
earlier intervention, follow a patient more precisely and more

38
00:02:07.980 --> 00:02:09.259
carefully over time.

39
00:02:10.361 --> 00:02:14.200
He has led pivotal studies that establish checkpoint immunotherapy as an effective

40
00:02:14.260 --> 00:02:17.600
treatment for patients with a particular type of genetic background, where their

41
00:02:17.660 --> 00:02:21.520
cancer has mismatch repair deficient or microsatellite

42
00:02:21.560 --> 00:02:25.040
instability-high cancers, making them extraordinarily susceptible

43
00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:28.260
to immune recognition and intervention.

44
00:02:28.920 --> 00:02:32.320
These studies supported the first FDA approval of a therapy based on a tumor's

45
00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:35.000
molecular features rather than its tissue

46
00:02:35.080 --> 00:02:38.420
of origin,

47
00:02:39.120 --> 00:02:42.700
a milestone that really has redefined the meaning of what we refer to as

48
00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:44.220
precise oncology.

49
00:02:45.680 --> 00:02:49.420
His discoveries have been translated into clinical innovations.

50
00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:51.940
He's co-founded several companies. Dr.

51
00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:55.250
Diaz's leadership extends across the academic oncology community.

52
00:02:56.020 --> 00:02:59.609
He serves as editor-in-chief of the AACR journal, "Cancer

53
00:02:59.660 --> 00:03:03.430
Discovery," previously served on the AACR Board of Directors,

54
00:03:03.920 --> 00:03:07.799
and was inducted as a fellow of the AACR Academy in 2022.

55
00:03:08.560 --> 00:03:12.300
He's been on the National Cancer Advisory Board, where he continues to

56
00:03:12.340 --> 00:03:16.310
contribute to shaping the national priorities for cancer research in

57
00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:16.910
this country.

58
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.220
Through his work in genomics, diagnostics, and immunotherapy, Dr.

59
00:03:21.300 --> 00:03:25.000
Diaz has advanced clinical research and improved outcomes for patients

60
00:03:25.020 --> 00:03:28.920
worldwide, making him a very appropriate recipient for this

61
00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:32.020
award, as I would say, in mid-career.

62
00:03:33.860 --> 00:03:37.540
It's my honor to introduce the 2026 recipient of the AACR Joseph

63
00:03:37.580 --> 00:03:40.800
Burkenau Award for Outstanding Achievement in Clinical Research, Dr.

64
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:42.440
Luis A. Diaz Jr.

65
00:03:45.620 --> 00:03:46.400
Thanks so much.

66
00:03:46.420 --> 00:03:46.990
You're very welcome.

67
00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:48.140
Thank you.

68
00:03:48.200 --> 00:03:48.880
Yeah, sure.

69
00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:53.960
Appreciate that.

70
00:03:56.480 --> 00:04:00.100
I appreciate the introduction and many thanks to the AACR, to you, and the

71
00:04:00.120 --> 00:04:02.060
committee for this honor.

72
00:04:03.300 --> 00:04:07.180
It's always a little awkward to get an award as an individual when

73
00:04:07.240 --> 00:04:09.400
all of this work was really done by teams.

74
00:04:09.420 --> 00:04:13.380
And there's an AACR Team Award, I think, that emblemizes a lot of things.

75
00:04:13.420 --> 00:04:17.370
But I thank the committee and the AACR because this is really a reflection

76
00:04:17.380 --> 00:04:18.981
on the teams that work on this work.

77
00:04:20.721 --> 00:04:22.680
I have to work on my disclosures here.

78
00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:28.900
And a bit about Joseph Burkenau. Whenever I look at

79
00:04:28.940 --> 00:04:31.560
these awards, I never spend the time to look up who

80
00:04:32.720 --> 00:04:36.660
the honoree really is or who it's named after.

81
00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:39.700
And I want to just review a little bit who Joseph Burkenau was, and you never

82
00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:41.500
really do it until you get an award like this.

83
00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:45.020
And he actually was a chemotherapy pioneer at Memorial Sloan Kettering, which is

84
00:04:45.800 --> 00:04:49.380
interesting because I work at Memorial Sloan Kettering, and he really helped make

85
00:04:49.420 --> 00:04:50.780
drug treatment a real path

86
00:04:51.800 --> 00:04:55.480
to cancer cure. He organized clinical chemotherapy program at MSK

87
00:04:56.020 --> 00:04:59.370
after World War II, helping define oncology as a distinct medical field and

88
00:04:59.420 --> 00:05:03.000
discipline. He co-developed mercaptopurine, an advanced combination

89
00:05:03.060 --> 00:05:04.780
chemotherapy for leukemia and lymphoma,

90
00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:09.630
helped launch the war on cancer, and shaped modern clinical oncology research,

91
00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:12.360
and won the 1972 Lasker Award.

92
00:05:14.580 --> 00:05:18.520
So I'm going to begin very basic and then dive into where some of

93
00:05:18.540 --> 00:05:20.060
this work really began

94
00:05:20.900 --> 00:05:23.280
to take shape. So how does cancer evolve?

95
00:05:23.320 --> 00:05:26.960
It evolves from a normal tissue, this is a normal colon, to a

96
00:05:26.980 --> 00:05:30.060
pre-malignant lesion, to an invasive lesion, to a metastatic lesion.

97
00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:34.420
If you look histologically, you see the classic changes from a

98
00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:37.580
precancerous adenoma to a large adenoma to an invasive carcinoma.

99
00:05:38.900 --> 00:05:42.860
If you look molecularly, you'll see the acquisition of mutations

100
00:05:43.060 --> 00:05:46.240
in a sequential, organized fashion, and key mutated genes

101
00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:50.300
increase regions of those genes that either activate genes for

102
00:05:50.480 --> 00:05:54.340
proliferation and growth or turn off genes that prevent cell

103
00:05:54.350 --> 00:05:54.660
death.

104
00:05:55.540 --> 00:05:59.280
Interesting thing is that at least in solid tumors, this doesn't occur overnight.

105
00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:02.710
This doesn't occur over a month or two or even a year.

106
00:06:02.800 --> 00:06:06.676
This occurs over a decade or two.And that gives us an opportunity

107
00:06:06.716 --> 00:06:09.856
and has given a lot of people opportunity to think about potentially early

108
00:06:09.896 --> 00:06:12.036
detection because this happens over a time span.

109
00:06:13.136 --> 00:06:16.996
And these mutations are defined by their presence in

110
00:06:17.056 --> 00:06:20.916
either cancer cells or pre-cancer cells called somatic

111
00:06:20.976 --> 00:06:24.916
mutations, and they're absent from the corresponding normal tissues.

112
00:06:26.656 --> 00:06:30.536
And really over the past 30 years, there has been

113
00:06:30.656 --> 00:06:30.796
a

114
00:06:32.856 --> 00:06:36.386
sequencing of tumors from the adults and children, men and women, and

115
00:06:36.416 --> 00:06:40.076
virtually every organism who has a cancer where we

116
00:06:40.116 --> 00:06:41.125
understand the cancer

117
00:06:42.756 --> 00:06:46.456
mutation landscape, and we have a mutational profile that's quite

118
00:06:46.496 --> 00:06:46.936
vast.

119
00:06:47.956 --> 00:06:51.356
And this somatic cancer genome data, so mutations just in the

120
00:06:51.396 --> 00:06:55.366
tumor and not in the corresponding normal tissue, can

121
00:06:55.396 --> 00:06:56.836
be used for a variety of different things.

122
00:06:56.896 --> 00:07:00.796
And my job after my postdoc when I joined a very basic

123
00:07:00.856 --> 00:07:04.676
science lab was, how can you take this information and use it clinically?

124
00:07:05.416 --> 00:07:08.596
And the hope was, one, maybe we'd have a predictive marker.

125
00:07:08.656 --> 00:07:12.396
We'd find a mutation, we marry that with a drug, and you'd cure the

126
00:07:12.436 --> 00:07:16.056
cancer. Really hard to do. And

127
00:07:16.396 --> 00:07:18.616
we have some examples, very hard to do.

128
00:07:19.356 --> 00:07:22.696
Next thing is you could take these mutations and look at

129
00:07:22.736 --> 00:07:26.376
prognosis. And one of the early mutations we discovered was

130
00:07:26.416 --> 00:07:26.936
IDH

131
00:07:27.776 --> 00:07:31.196
in gliomas, and that was a better prognosis than those without IDH

132
00:07:31.276 --> 00:07:33.926
mutations. But two of the areas that I think

133
00:07:34.776 --> 00:07:38.126
we began to think about as a group, and this was when I was at Johns Hopkins,

134
00:07:38.636 --> 00:07:42.596
was could you take these mutations and either use them as diagnostic

135
00:07:42.696 --> 00:07:43.096
tools

136
00:07:43.976 --> 00:07:47.876
in a dynamic way in biofluids, liquid biopsy.

137
00:07:48.716 --> 00:07:52.156
And the other way to look at them was, could these mutations in the

138
00:07:52.216 --> 00:07:56.086
context of an expressed protein be an immune antigen and stimulate the

139
00:07:56.116 --> 00:08:00.016
immune system in a unique way? And so I'll take you primarily through the

140
00:08:00.036 --> 00:08:00.996
immune antigen story,

141
00:08:01.896 --> 00:08:05.196
but there's a vast background and history to the liquid biopsy story as well.

142
00:08:06.916 --> 00:08:10.776
And the immune oncology story really began

143
00:08:11.816 --> 00:08:15.156
with these two papers. I joined a cancer genetics lab

144
00:08:15.795 --> 00:08:19.636
because I never thought the immune system would ever work to treat solid tumor

145
00:08:19.676 --> 00:08:23.436
oncology. And I was very confident in that until these two

146
00:08:23.476 --> 00:08:25.036
papers showed up.

147
00:08:26.496 --> 00:08:29.916
This was checkpoint blockade with Ipi Milab against

148
00:08:29.936 --> 00:08:32.136
CTLA-4 in metastatic melanoma showing response,

149
00:08:33.236 --> 00:08:37.036
and then anti-PD-1. And it wasn't the response in

150
00:08:37.076 --> 00:08:40.817
melanoma or also kidney cancer that surprised me or that

151
00:08:40.876 --> 00:08:44.626
interested me. Those are immunogenic tumors, not surprising at

152
00:08:44.696 --> 00:08:48.636
all. What surprised me and the whole field was we

153
00:08:48.645 --> 00:08:52.126
were starting to see responses in lung cancer, and that was

154
00:08:52.176 --> 00:08:55.616
unique. These tumors are like rocks, and I didn't think the immune system

155
00:08:55.656 --> 00:08:59.436
could at all change the outcome of these patients, and we started to see those

156
00:08:59.476 --> 00:09:02.636
outcomes. So that piqued our interest.

157
00:09:02.756 --> 00:09:06.406
And the laboratory had been focusing a lot

158
00:09:06.556 --> 00:09:09.536
on cancer exome sequencing of solid tumors.

159
00:09:10.796 --> 00:09:13.356
And with work with Bert Vogelstein, Nick Papadopoulos,

160
00:09:14.576 --> 00:09:14.796
and

161
00:09:15.676 --> 00:09:19.036
Nick Papadopoulos, whose sentencing right there we describe

162
00:09:19.296 --> 00:09:22.576
the sequence of a variety of different tumors, liquid tumors, pediatric

163
00:09:22.616 --> 00:09:26.206
tumors, sporadic adult tumors, mutagen-induced tumors,

164
00:09:26.636 --> 00:09:27.996
and then mismatch repair-deficient tumors.

165
00:09:28.756 --> 00:09:32.176
And simply counting the number of mutations from tumor type, you could see there

166
00:09:32.196 --> 00:09:32.916
was a big difference.

167
00:09:33.956 --> 00:09:37.736
And what was interesting to us is that at the time, melanoma and lung cancers,

168
00:09:38.276 --> 00:09:41.636
we found had many more mutations than sporadic tumors.

169
00:09:41.676 --> 00:09:43.156
And these were the tumors that were responding.

170
00:09:44.136 --> 00:09:47.896
So it set up a question which is, could a tumor type with

171
00:09:47.976 --> 00:09:49.036
many more mutations

172
00:09:49.896 --> 00:09:51.576
potentially be more immunogenic?

173
00:09:52.816 --> 00:09:56.546
And so a little bit about mismatch repair-deficient tumors and microsatellite

174
00:09:56.556 --> 00:09:58.976
instability, because they're two sides of the same coin.

175
00:10:00.056 --> 00:10:03.676
Mismatch repair deficiency comes in two forms, a hereditary form called Lynch

176
00:10:03.736 --> 00:10:07.536
syndrome and a sporadic form. With a hereditary form, you inherit

177
00:10:07.656 --> 00:10:11.296
one allele that's inactivated, and you acquire a second allele during

178
00:10:11.336 --> 00:10:15.076
early pre-adenoma development, and then you lose the second allele.

179
00:10:15.166 --> 00:10:18.216
Sporadic, you lose both during oncogenesis.

180
00:10:19.556 --> 00:10:21.816
The hereditary form is rarer than the sporadic form.

181
00:10:23.615 --> 00:10:27.576
And when you have inactivation of mismatch repair, it leads during DNA

182
00:10:27.616 --> 00:10:31.136
replication an inability to recognize and repair

183
00:10:31.296 --> 00:10:34.676
spontaneous mutations, either single base pair mutations or short insertions and

184
00:10:34.696 --> 00:10:35.116
deletions.

185
00:10:36.396 --> 00:10:38.556
And then this leads to

186
00:10:40.436 --> 00:10:43.966
accumulation of mutations, ultramicrosatellites, and then

187
00:10:43.996 --> 00:10:47.756
eventually MSI and TMB. So if you're

188
00:10:47.776 --> 00:10:49.236
mismatch repair deficient on day one,

189
00:10:50.136 --> 00:10:52.176
you're not going to be high TMB the next day.

190
00:10:52.856 --> 00:10:54.776
You're not going to be high TMB the next month.

191
00:10:55.396 --> 00:10:57.396
It's going to take years for that to develop.

192
00:10:57.876 --> 00:11:01.736
Likewise, you're not MSI the day after you are mismatch repair deficient.

193
00:11:02.316 --> 00:11:04.736
You're MSI many months or years later.

194
00:11:05.056 --> 00:11:07.196
So this is a process that accumulates over time.

195
00:11:09.216 --> 00:11:11.976
And taking you a little bit back to the history,

196
00:11:13.836 --> 00:11:17.736
there was a long history in understanding these hereditary mutations, which

197
00:11:17.776 --> 00:11:20.396
gave us the first clues of what mismatch repair deficiency was.

198
00:11:21.276 --> 00:11:24.536
And this is work done by Albert de la Chapelle and one of my mentors, Bert

199
00:11:24.596 --> 00:11:25.096
Vogelstein,

200
00:11:26.476 --> 00:11:29.936
in showing that these familial cancers had widespread

201
00:11:29.976 --> 00:11:31.536
alterations in microsatellites,

202
00:11:32.676 --> 00:11:36.656
and that these microsatellites, when they were altered, are more common

203
00:11:36.756 --> 00:11:37.796
in the familiar form

204
00:11:38.816 --> 00:11:42.656
and frequently altered in the familiar form than the non-familiar form of

205
00:11:42.696 --> 00:11:43.756
mismatch repair deficiency.

206
00:11:44.756 --> 00:11:48.656
And Nick, who I highlighted before was the first to describe

207
00:11:48.716 --> 00:11:50.276
one of the hereditary mutations

208
00:11:52.196 --> 00:11:56.056
that inactivated mismatch repair in Lynch

209
00:11:56.076 --> 00:11:56.416
syndrome.

210
00:11:58.516 --> 00:12:02.456
And then when further looking at these, they found that there was a

211
00:12:02.496 --> 00:12:03.916
hypermutability of these tumors.

212
00:12:03.966 --> 00:12:07.876
And this is back in 1993 when the...

213
00:12:07.906 --> 00:12:10.125
mutations and hypermutability was really

214
00:12:10.936 --> 00:12:13.596
defined by very different tools than we use today.

215
00:12:14.116 --> 00:12:15.836
And so you can see this is about 1993.

216
00:12:17.556 --> 00:12:20.296
In parallel, and this is all happening at Johns Hopkins at the time,

217
00:12:21.536 --> 00:12:25.496
Stan Hamilton, a pathologist, described something that all

218
00:12:25.536 --> 00:12:26.316
pathologists knew.

219
00:12:27.236 --> 00:12:31.216
If you have a patient with a hereditary colon cancer, oftentimes they had a rich

220
00:12:31.576 --> 00:12:35.206
lymphocytic infiltrate. And what he defined were that these mismatch repair

221
00:12:35.236 --> 00:12:39.206
deficient tumors were often inflamed and infiltrated with lymphocytes.

222
00:12:39.756 --> 00:12:43.656
So setting up the stage for an immunogenic response

223
00:12:43.696 --> 00:12:45.636
going on there. So 1994.

224
00:12:47.856 --> 00:12:51.556
Not much happened from 1994 till those two papers came out in

225
00:12:51.596 --> 00:12:54.056
PD-1 blockade. Primarily worked on

226
00:12:54.876 --> 00:12:58.716
identifying and screening for Lynch syndrome for screening purposes,

227
00:12:59.096 --> 00:13:02.576
and there was a lot of work done there, but on the therapeutic angle.

228
00:13:02.586 --> 00:13:06.336
And so the hypothesis that we had when we saw the cancer genomics

229
00:13:06.356 --> 00:13:10.276
work and the immunotherapy responses, primarily in lung cancer,

230
00:13:10.436 --> 00:13:14.416
was if these genomes of mismatch repair tumors had thousands of mutations,

231
00:13:15.396 --> 00:13:19.136
if these mutations happen to be expressed as proteins,

232
00:13:20.076 --> 00:13:23.836
would that induce a foreign-looking tumor to the immune system?

233
00:13:24.916 --> 00:13:28.516
And if that foreignness was controlled by

234
00:13:28.556 --> 00:13:32.456
upregulation of immune checkpoints, could you treat them with immune

235
00:13:32.516 --> 00:13:36.096
checkpoint blockade? We knew they were highly inflamed and could this treatment

236
00:13:36.106 --> 00:13:40.096
with immune checkpoint blockade lead to a very potent antitumor response.

237
00:13:41.036 --> 00:13:41.236
So

238
00:13:42.736 --> 00:13:43.956
when we had this idea,

239
00:13:45.196 --> 00:13:48.596
we were primarily a research lab. We didn't know how to run clinical trials, so we

240
00:13:48.636 --> 00:13:52.336
recruited Yung Li, who was a junior assistant, actually, a newly minted

241
00:13:52.356 --> 00:13:55.456
assistant professor, because she would be the only one that listened to us.

242
00:13:56.636 --> 00:14:00.576
And we didn't have money, we didn't have a drug, but we had now an investigator

243
00:14:00.596 --> 00:14:04.136
and an idea. And we designed this idea

244
00:14:05.076 --> 00:14:08.676
on a whiteboard that we would take colon cancers, the most common tumor type with

245
00:14:08.716 --> 00:14:09.576
mismatch repair deficiency,

246
00:14:10.476 --> 00:14:14.276
and take a cohort that was mismatch repair deficient, take

