00:20:10.300 --> 00:20:13.160
monitor tumor growth in mice

353
00:20:14.920 --> 00:20:18.520
without having to just... Because we thought calipers were very inaccurate.

354
00:20:18.619 --> 00:20:22.120
If we had metastatic models that were very inaccurate to measure growth, or

355
00:20:22.300 --> 00:20:24.180
bioluminescence was just coming into vogue.

356
00:20:24.740 --> 00:20:28.140
So could you do a p***k to the tail vein, get a drop of blood,

357
00:20:28.640 --> 00:20:32.040
dilute that in EDTA, separate the cell-free DNA,

358
00:20:32.860 --> 00:20:35.620
and then measure that, this is a xenograft for human

359
00:20:36.800 --> 00:20:37.060
DNA,

360
00:20:37.940 --> 00:20:39.540
and this one line one element that

361
00:20:40.500 --> 00:20:44.300
is sequences exclusive to the mouse, and could you track the tumor

362
00:20:44.340 --> 00:20:47.240
growth and response of therapies?

363
00:20:47.260 --> 00:20:48.970
And we did a simple experiment to look at this.

364
00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:52.740
So we looked at human line

365
00:20:52.900 --> 00:20:55.400
one. We created a small amplicon, and we could measure that in mice.

366
00:20:55.409 --> 00:20:57.340
And so as the tumor grew, it increased in size.

367
00:20:57.960 --> 00:20:58.960
But if you cut out the tumor,

368
00:21:00.240 --> 00:21:03.000
it went down to zero, and it went down to zero almost immediately.

369
00:21:03.260 --> 00:21:04.920
And so you can see here the tumor is growing.

370
00:21:05.940 --> 00:21:08.800
We resect it, and it goes down to zero. It goes down to zero.

371
00:21:08.860 --> 00:21:12.480
The half-life of these fragments were about two hours.

372
00:21:12.540 --> 00:21:14.060
And so it set up the next question.

373
00:21:15.640 --> 00:21:18.800
Could we look at circulating mutant DNA in humans?

374
00:21:19.060 --> 00:21:22.960
And so there were some techniques that were developed at this time, and

375
00:21:22.980 --> 00:21:26.620
this is the first example of that. So this was published in 2008,

376
00:21:27.120 --> 00:21:28.400
and Frank Dio is the first author.

377
00:21:29.320 --> 00:21:32.580
What we did here was take a technique called beaming, and this is looking at a

378
00:21:32.640 --> 00:21:33.400
single mutation

379
00:21:34.940 --> 00:21:35.360
by single

380
00:21:36.440 --> 00:21:40.360
base extension using a technique that is resolved by

