00:27:33.232 --> 00:27:36.952
or moderate-sized populations relative to the current adjuvant studies, which take

488
00:27:37.032 --> 00:27:40.432
thousands of patients. And I think that's going to be a big improvement in

489
00:27:40.472 --> 00:27:42.412
studying the adjuvant therapeutics.

490
00:27:44.172 --> 00:27:44.312
So

491
00:27:45.172 --> 00:27:48.612
we talked about metastatic patients, we talked about the adjuvant setting,

492
00:27:49.292 --> 00:27:51.672
and one thing when I was reading about Dr.

493
00:27:51.852 --> 00:27:55.532
Burchenal is that he really believed cancer, like infections, could be cured

494
00:27:56.052 --> 00:27:59.972
by rational multidrug or even single-drug therapy guided by careful trials

495
00:28:00.072 --> 00:28:01.532
rather than fatalism. At the time,

496
00:28:02.792 --> 00:28:04.092
no one liked chemotherapy, right?

497
00:28:04.122 --> 00:28:06.472
And they thought chemotherapy was a terrible thing.

498
00:28:06.501 --> 00:28:09.432
And obviously back then, the chemotherapy is very different than what we have now.

499
00:28:10.652 --> 00:28:14.512
But he had a formal training in tropical medicine

500
00:28:14.552 --> 00:28:18.292
after World War II, and his mindset was you could

501
00:28:18.352 --> 00:28:21.792
cure these systemic diseases or even these localized diseases with chemotherapy.

502
00:28:21.872 --> 00:28:21.972
So

503
00:28:23.252 --> 00:28:25.812
we had shown some of that today, but I'm going to show you a little bit more.

504
00:28:26.832 --> 00:28:28.712
And I'm going to move on to early-stage cancers.

505
00:28:29.772 --> 00:28:31.812
This is one of the patients that we treated.

506
00:28:32.632 --> 00:28:34.552
And so early-stage cancer. So

507
00:28:35.812 --> 00:28:39.702
I removed the background slide here on rectal cancer, but one of the things

508
00:28:39.752 --> 00:28:43.252
that is always troubling when you have an early-stage patient is even though you

509
00:28:43.292 --> 00:28:44.232
can cure a patient,

510
00:28:45.272 --> 00:28:47.172
if that tumor sits in an organ

511
00:28:48.192 --> 00:28:52.102
where that curative resection is life-altering,

512
00:28:52.672 --> 00:28:56.332
like in the esophagus or in the stomach or in the bladder or in the

513
00:28:56.352 --> 00:29:00.232
rectum, there is going to be a life-altering change to that patient,

514
00:29:00.292 --> 00:29:04.192
even though we cured them. And in rectal cancer, it's one of those cases where

515
00:29:04.552 --> 00:29:08.372
you not only deliver chemotherapy and radiation and then

516
00:29:08.432 --> 00:29:11.792
surgical resection of the rectum, but in a large number of patients, they have an

517
00:29:11.872 --> 00:29:12.252
ostomy,

518
00:29:13.352 --> 00:29:16.842
there's sexual dysfunction, GU dysfunction,

519
00:29:17.712 --> 00:29:21.622
and that's lifelong. And so we designed a study with

520
00:29:21.652 --> 00:29:25.632
Andrea Sercik where we took early-stage, locally advanced rectal

521
00:29:25.692 --> 00:29:29.212
cancers, and we took patients that were mismatched or deficient,

522
00:29:29.632 --> 00:29:31.452
treated them with six months of PD-1 blockade,

523
00:29:32.472 --> 00:29:36.332
and then evaluated them to see if

524
00:29:36.532 --> 00:29:40.112
we were going to go forward with standard of care therapy or not.

525
00:29:40.272 --> 00:29:43.312
And if there was residual disease, we went with standard of care therapy with

526
00:29:43.332 --> 00:29:45.612
chemotherapy, then radiation and surgery.

527
00:29:47.402 --> 00:29:51.352
With every project, there's a moment where the project

528
00:29:51.432 --> 00:29:55.152
goes from, "Oh, this will be another neoadjuvant or another type of

529
00:29:55.572 --> 00:29:59.182
therapy or project that's more standard, or one that can potentially,

530
00:29:59.652 --> 00:30:03.292
if you're lucky, it can be a world-class alt change." And

531
00:30:03.372 --> 00:30:06.732
Andrea felt very strongly that if the patients had a complete response,

532
00:30:07.372 --> 00:30:08.932
she didn't want to force them to have surgery.

533
00:30:10.052 --> 00:30:13.482
Because could you imagine? You get treated, you have a complete response,

534
00:30:13.572 --> 00:30:17.472
and then you remove the rectum. And so we decided to put this

535
00:30:17.492 --> 00:30:20.892
arm in. If the patient has a complete clinical response, which was a paradigm that

536
00:30:20.932 --> 00:30:24.632
was understood before with chemotherapy and radiation,

537
00:30:24.892 --> 00:30:27.682
that they couldGo forward with non-operative management.

538
00:30:29.062 --> 00:30:30.462
And so this was the first patient treated,

539
00:30:31.702 --> 00:30:35.362
and you see there a large tumor in the rectum visible by MRI and PET.

540
00:30:36.162 --> 00:30:39.522
At six weeks, the tumor has quite a good response.

541
00:30:40.442 --> 00:30:44.052
And then at three months, six months, and then throughout 24 months,

542
00:30:44.462 --> 00:30:47.642
the tumor's disappeared. The MRI is normalized, and so is the PET scan.

543
00:30:49.142 --> 00:30:51.282
First patient, bulky T4 tumor,

544
00:30:52.322 --> 00:30:54.592
positive lymph nodes, complete clinical response.

545
00:30:55.902 --> 00:30:58.931
And then the subsequent 13 patients all had the same thing.

546
00:30:59.462 --> 00:31:03.372
The tumors melted away after six months of therapy, and there was

547
00:31:03.402 --> 00:31:04.242
no visible tumor

548
00:31:05.162 --> 00:31:07.422
by imaging, by pathology,

549
00:31:08.662 --> 00:31:10.442
by visual inspection,

550
00:31:11.282 --> 00:31:13.302
and the patients all did quite well.

551
00:31:14.522 --> 00:31:18.022
So what resulted from that is none of those patients required

552
00:31:18.062 --> 00:31:21.682
chemotherapy, none of them required radiation, and none of them required

553
00:31:21.722 --> 00:31:22.071
surgery,

554
00:31:23.202 --> 00:31:26.082
which was remarkable, and I think probably one of the first times that's happened

555
00:31:26.102 --> 00:31:26.822
in oncology.

556
00:31:28.162 --> 00:31:31.542
But the question was next, could this extend beyond rectal cancer?

557
00:31:31.822 --> 00:31:35.802
Because as we know, these tumors occur that are mismatch repair deficient beyond

558
00:31:35.812 --> 00:31:36.302
the rectum.

559
00:31:37.112 --> 00:31:40.912
And so the question is, could we go forward with non-operative management in those

560
00:31:40.922 --> 00:31:41.252
tumors?

561
00:31:42.122 --> 00:31:43.762
And what's the durability of this?

562
00:31:43.822 --> 00:31:47.072
Is this just the tumors disappear and they come right back, or do they stay away?

563
00:31:48.082 --> 00:31:51.682
And so we designed the same study, but with tumors from anywhere else in the body.

564
00:31:52.482 --> 00:31:55.742
And we accrued patients that were not only rectal cancer, but

565
00:31:55.782 --> 00:31:58.282
throughout other organs in the body.

566
00:31:58.312 --> 00:32:02.162
And we really wanted to emphasize on tumors where the surgery was really

567
00:32:02.182 --> 00:32:02.902
life altering.

568
00:32:04.402 --> 00:32:06.342
And so we enrolled 124 patients.

569
00:32:07.462 --> 00:32:10.062
At the time of publication, 117 were evaluable,

570
00:32:11.022 --> 00:32:14.822
and 103 completed treatment. And we had a cohort of rectal cancer patients,

571
00:32:15.202 --> 00:32:16.012
49, and

572
00:32:16.902 --> 00:32:18.342
54 non-rectal cancer patients.

573
00:32:19.782 --> 00:32:20.022
This is

574
00:32:21.362 --> 00:32:22.142
pretty remarkable.

575
00:32:23.082 --> 00:32:25.402
Thirty-five percent of patients had no adverse events.

576
00:32:27.122 --> 00:32:29.642
I think most of us could go to the gym and trigger

577
00:32:30.362 --> 00:32:33.322
alteration that would be toxicity,

578
00:32:34.222 --> 00:32:37.882
but 35% had none. And that's pretty remarkable, and that sets up

579
00:32:37.942 --> 00:32:39.962
another scenario for down the road.

580
00:32:40.482 --> 00:32:41.942
And the toxicity was quite minimal.

581
00:32:44.002 --> 00:32:47.882
So when we looked at the rectal cancer cohort, all 49 had a complete

582
00:32:47.942 --> 00:32:50.862
clinical response, and all went for non-operative management,

583
00:32:52.362 --> 00:32:53.142
so 100%.

584
00:32:55.122 --> 00:32:57.992
And in terms of recurrence-free survival, we've been following these patients for a

585
00:32:58.002 --> 00:33:01.582
while in the range from five months to five years.

586
00:33:02.182 --> 00:33:05.542
And this median follow-up here is quite well, and 96 were recurrence-free at two

587
00:33:05.602 --> 00:33:05.842
years.

588
00:33:08.302 --> 00:33:09.662
In terms of the non-rectal cohort,

589
00:33:10.622 --> 00:33:14.382
we had 35 with complete clinical response and 19 with incomplete

590
00:33:14.422 --> 00:33:15.042
responses.

591
00:33:17.122 --> 00:33:20.822
In the complete clinical response, even though the tumor was gone, two patients

592
00:33:21.262 --> 00:33:22.042
opted for surgery,

593
00:33:22.862 --> 00:33:23.442
human nature,

594
00:33:24.602 --> 00:33:26.422
and 33 went for non-operative management.

595
00:33:28.102 --> 00:33:31.742
In the incomplete clinical responses, 16 went for

596
00:33:31.822 --> 00:33:35.562
surgery, three did not. Again, human nature, they

597
00:33:35.582 --> 00:33:37.512
refused surgery despite having tumor left,

598
00:33:38.942 --> 00:33:39.842
which I find interesting.

599
00:33:41.282 --> 00:33:43.602
But here we see heterogeneity in the response.

600
00:33:43.682 --> 00:33:47.002
So in urothelial cancers, they all responded completely.

601
00:33:47.882 --> 00:33:48.682
Hepatobiliary,

602
00:33:49.682 --> 00:33:53.182
pancreatic biliary, they all responded well. Colon, a little bit less well.

603
00:33:53.302 --> 00:33:57.242
Gastric, a little bit less well. And then GI junction, EG, small bowel, and then

604
00:33:57.252 --> 00:33:59.222
endometrium, prostate, not responding as well.

605
00:33:59.502 --> 00:34:03.052
Small numbers, but framing the idea and the

606
00:34:03.142 --> 00:34:06.722
concept that we could take these tumors

607
00:34:07.362 --> 00:34:11.283
that were mismatch or deficient and maybe avoid surgery in a large

608
00:34:11.322 --> 00:34:14.243
majority of them because they respond so well to immune checkpoint blockade.

609
00:34:14.303 --> 00:34:16.942
So 85% were recurrence-free at two years.

610
00:34:18.922 --> 00:34:22.723
And so going forward, and if you fast-forward to the future,

611
00:34:23.263 --> 00:34:27.002
how do you bring this to the general population of

612
00:34:27.362 --> 00:34:29.533
oncologists and surgeons, and how do you track this?

613
00:34:30.152 --> 00:34:33.263
And I think one of the ways to track this that's quite effective and quite

614
00:34:33.303 --> 00:34:33.772
sensitive,

615
00:34:35.033 --> 00:34:38.553
is using circulating tumor DNA. What we found was that in complete responses, you

616
00:34:38.642 --> 00:34:41.203
see normalization of circulating tumor DNA.

617
00:34:41.223 --> 00:34:44.562
By the end of treatment, those that were CT negative at the time,

618
00:34:45.743 --> 00:34:48.662
no longer had tumor, and they had complete responses.

619
00:34:49.422 --> 00:34:53.223
Incomplete responses, you see this chaotic drop in circulating

620
00:34:53.243 --> 00:34:55.462
tumor DNA. Not all of them are cured.

621
00:34:56.542 --> 00:34:59.522
And these are tumor remains after immune checkpoint blockade.

622
00:34:59.882 --> 00:35:03.702
And even in the recurrences, you see again, the persistence of circulating tumor

623
00:35:03.712 --> 00:35:06.582
DNA despite having a complete response.

624
00:35:06.642 --> 00:35:08.622
This is just another way of looking at it.

625
00:35:09.582 --> 00:35:12.322
The complete responses go to zero by six months or end of treatment.

626
00:35:12.922 --> 00:35:16.662
The incomplete responses and recurrences have persistent circulating tumor DNA.

627
00:35:16.802 --> 00:35:20.682
So this may be a tool we can use to track who can get non-operative

628
00:35:20.762 --> 00:35:21.602
management and who can't.

629
00:35:22.572 --> 00:35:26.402
And when you look at more traditional modalities like imaging and endoscopies,

630
00:35:27.082 --> 00:35:30.212
not only are they slow to define a complete clinical response,

631
00:35:31.542 --> 00:35:33.382
but they're not as specific or sensitive.

632
00:35:34.062 --> 00:35:38.002
And the earliest ways you can really get this is by a biopsy of the tissue

633
00:35:38.042 --> 00:35:40.902
itself, where the tumor bed is, or circulating tumor DNA.

634
00:35:41.042 --> 00:35:42.862
So I think circulating tumor DNA has some promise here.

635
00:35:44.822 --> 00:35:48.162
So future directions. So based on this data,

636
00:35:49.482 --> 00:35:53.242
I think there's going to be a massive reduction in cancer surgeries in the next

637
00:35:53.282 --> 00:35:53.742
five years.

638
00:35:55.002 --> 00:35:56.182
But I think there's going to be more.

639
00:35:56.982 --> 00:36:00.422
I think there's going to be the possibility of therapeutic cancer prevention.

640
00:36:01.282 --> 00:36:05.242
And I'll show you some clues to why we think this is possible. So immunoprevention.

641
00:36:06.842 --> 00:36:07.562
So there

642
00:36:08.562 --> 00:36:11.662
are 1.5 million Lynch syndrome patients in the US currently.

643
00:36:12.482 --> 00:36:16.362
These are patients who harbor the risk but not all have cancer.

644
00:36:17.162 --> 00:36:21.062
The risk of secondary primary malignancy after the first one is 4% per mean

645
00:36:21.122 --> 00:36:21.962
observation years.

646
00:36:23.102 --> 00:36:24.922
And risk varies by germline genotype.

647
00:36:26.702 --> 00:36:28.012
So the question we had was,

648
00:36:29.102 --> 00:36:32.774
could PD-1 blockade prevent cancer?And

649
00:36:33.314 --> 00:36:33.474
we

650
00:36:34.294 --> 00:36:37.474
formulated two questions. One is, could it impact polyp formation?

651
00:36:38.714 --> 00:36:40.094
And the second is, could it delay

652
00:36:41.074 --> 00:36:44.954
cancer or tumor formation? And this is work that we worked on with Sophia

653
00:36:44.994 --> 00:36:46.614
Stadler, Emily Herald,

654
00:36:47.754 --> 00:36:47.974
and this

655
00:36:49.074 --> 00:36:50.694
brought this together quite nicely.

656
00:36:51.494 --> 00:36:55.414
So at Memorial, they had a registry of 837 Lynch syndrome

657
00:36:55.474 --> 00:36:57.714
patients. Most of these had

658
00:36:58.594 --> 00:37:02.414
cancer. Six hundred and sixty-five did not receive

659
00:37:02.454 --> 00:37:05.454
immune checkpoint blockade, but 172 did.

660
00:37:06.814 --> 00:37:10.474
And so first question, would immune checkpoint blockade alter polyp

661
00:37:10.514 --> 00:37:13.874
formation in Lynch syndrome patients?

662
00:37:13.914 --> 00:37:17.254
And so we didn't see a difference in those that received immune checkpoint blockade

663
00:37:17.294 --> 00:37:17.694
or not,

664
00:37:18.634 --> 00:37:20.454
in terms of baseline incidence of polyps,

665
00:37:22.974 --> 00:37:26.724
or the adenomas per colonoscopy. So answering the question to us

666
00:37:27.234 --> 00:37:30.724
that no, immune checkpoint blockade did not impact polyp formation.

667
00:37:31.534 --> 00:37:34.994
Now, if we were smart, we would have known the answer to this before we even asked

668
00:37:35.034 --> 00:37:38.864
the question. Most polyps in mismatch repair deficient tumors or patients with

669
00:37:39.234 --> 00:37:41.074
Lynch syndrome are MSS.

670
00:37:42.194 --> 00:37:45.824
And so they're not classically immunogenic by our criteria.

671
00:37:46.734 --> 00:37:47.594
But what about cancer?

672
00:37:48.554 --> 00:37:52.334
And so we looked at patients who were at high risk, and this was actually an

673
00:37:52.374 --> 00:37:54.144
observation made by Benoit Rousseau.

674
00:37:54.894 --> 00:37:57.334
And these are patients that did not receive immune checkpoint blockade.

675
00:37:57.354 --> 00:38:00.734
And this is a cumulative incidence of cancer in these patients.

676
00:38:00.804 --> 00:38:03.694
And these are patients that had one or two cancers previously.

677
00:38:04.374 --> 00:38:07.034
But what if you received immune checkpoint blockade? What could happen?

678
00:38:08.494 --> 00:38:11.874
Well, there was a dramatic reduction in the incidence of cancer in these patients

679
00:38:12.294 --> 00:38:14.434
as a secondary event after the primary cancers.

680
00:38:15.054 --> 00:38:18.714
And so setting up the stage that while we couldn't inhibit polyp

681
00:38:18.754 --> 00:38:22.674
formation, we can maybe prevent cancer from developing

682
00:38:22.694 --> 00:38:23.394
in these patients.

683
00:38:24.674 --> 00:38:28.634
And this was a fairly long time after the administration of immune

684
00:38:28.674 --> 00:38:32.624
checkpoint blockade in these patients, so there's quite a long effect with earlier

685
00:38:32.714 --> 00:38:33.074
treatment.

686
00:38:34.814 --> 00:38:36.394
And so this is just another way of looking at it.

687
00:38:36.614 --> 00:38:39.994
Those that receive immune checkpoint blockade versus those that don't, there's a

688
00:38:40.074 --> 00:38:43.794
greater than 80% reduction in the incidence of cancer as a preventative

689
00:38:43.854 --> 00:38:46.124
approach in a retrospective evaluation.

690
00:38:47.384 --> 00:38:49.274
Tells us a little bit about the biology as well.

691
00:38:50.474 --> 00:38:52.434
Normal tissue, typically non-immunogenic.

692
00:38:53.394 --> 00:38:56.574
Premalignant tissue, adenoma in this case, were non-immunogenic.

693
00:38:56.614 --> 00:38:57.914
They weren't cleared by anti-PD-1.

694
00:38:58.714 --> 00:39:02.274
But given the history in early stage mismatch repair deficient tumors,

695
00:39:02.514 --> 00:39:06.454
highly immunogenic, and they become a little less immunogenic once they become

696
00:39:06.494 --> 00:39:07.094
metastatic.

697
00:39:08.234 --> 00:39:12.074
And we have some clues here that I think that I didn't highlight specifically,

698
00:39:12.094 --> 00:39:15.554
but if you look at three different compartments, the distant

699
00:39:15.594 --> 00:39:19.354
metastasis, the lymph node bed around the tumor, and the

700
00:39:19.394 --> 00:39:20.414
primary tumor itself,

701
00:39:21.294 --> 00:39:23.354
the primary tumor itself responds beautifully.

702
00:39:24.034 --> 00:39:25.434
You can clear that primary tumor

703
00:39:26.334 --> 00:39:29.174
fairly easily with immune checkpoint blockade if you're mismatch repair deficient.

704
00:39:30.314 --> 00:39:33.114
The metastasis, you'll clear about 50% to 60% of the time.

705
00:39:34.034 --> 00:39:35.794
The lymph node, somewhere in between.

706
00:39:36.014 --> 00:39:39.624
So these different microenvironments respond very differently

707
00:39:40.454 --> 00:39:41.694
when you're thinking about cure

708
00:39:43.114 --> 00:39:44.574
than individual regions.

709
00:39:46.674 --> 00:39:50.194
So in summary about prevention, it doesn't inhibit polyp formation, but it does

710
00:39:50.494 --> 00:39:53.954
slow tumor development, especially in high-risk patients.

711
00:39:55.614 --> 00:39:58.874
And the data all suggests that immunogenicity develops over time

712
00:39:59.434 --> 00:40:01.534
and in different compartments in the body.

713
00:40:01.754 --> 00:40:04.214
This may open the door for immunoprevention.

714
00:40:04.254 --> 00:40:07.834
So one study that we're about to

715
00:40:07.894 --> 00:40:11.734
launch is a randomized study in Lynch syndrome patients of PD-1

716
00:40:11.774 --> 00:40:12.994
blockade versus placebo.

717
00:40:14.154 --> 00:40:16.554
And we're just working out some of the details here, but I think that this could

718
00:40:16.654 --> 00:40:19.854
have a big impact in immunoprevention for this population.

719
00:40:20.514 --> 00:40:24.034
And I think that we're going to be seeing a much

720
00:40:24.314 --> 00:40:28.214
larger amount of preventative studies across the board for cancers, just not

721
00:40:28.254 --> 00:40:29.734
in Lynch syndrome, but across the board.

722
00:40:30.894 --> 00:40:33.674
So therapeutic cancer prevention, I think, is another future direction.

723
00:40:34.043 --> 00:40:37.994
And so what's the third one? The third one is cancer re-engineering.

724
00:40:38.043 --> 00:40:41.794
And what do I mean by that? And I'm not going to talk a lot about this, but the

725
00:40:41.834 --> 00:40:43.614
current therapeutic paradigm is passive.

726
00:40:44.434 --> 00:40:45.454
Patient comes to our door,

727
00:40:46.414 --> 00:40:48.494
they have a genetic alteration, and we treat them.

728
00:40:49.394 --> 00:40:52.894
So we're rolling the dice when the patient walks in the door.

729
00:40:53.233 --> 00:40:55.174
They have no control of it. We have no control of it.

730
00:40:55.234 --> 00:40:57.754
It's whatever's in front of us. And so the tumor

731
00:40:59.114 --> 00:41:02.134
plus target, we give a certain therapy, and we wait for therapy response.

732
00:41:02.754 --> 00:41:03.894
What if we did something different?

733
00:41:04.014 --> 00:41:07.694
What if we give a therapy to hack the tumor, to create a target,

734
